## Implementation Steps

### Step 1 — Scaffold the Nuxt 3 project
- Run `npx nuxi@latest init .` in the repo root.
- Install Tailwind CSS (`npm install -D tailwindcss @tailwindcss/vite`).
- Verify `npm run dev` works with a blank page.

### Step 2 — Define the motivator data model
- Create `config/motivators.ts` with a typed list of available motivators:

```ts
export interface Motivator {
  id: string
  name: string
  avatar?: string   // path to image in public/
  description?: string
}

export const motivators: Motivator[] = [
  { id: 'oystein', name: 'Øystein Pettersen' },
  { id: 'jon', name: 'Jon Almås' },
]
```

- Adding a new motivator = adding one entry to this array.

### Step 3 — Build `pages/index.vue` (Main View)

```
<template>
  ┌─────────────────────────────────┐
  │  <h1> HuMotivatoren </h1>       │  ← Large heading, centered
  │                                 │
  │  <img/svg> Face character       │  ← Illustrated face/avatar
  │  <p> "Hva skal jeg motivere     │  ← Speech bubble with question
  │       deg til idag?" </p>       │
  │                                 │
  │  <textarea v-model="task" />    │  ← Text input for the situation
  │                                 │
  │  <MotivatorPicker               │  ← Select your motivator
  │    v-model="selectedMotivator"  │
  │    :motivators="motivators" />  │
  │                                 │
  │  <button                        │  ← Submit (disabled until both
  │    :disabled="!canSubmit"       │     task + motivator are set)
  │    @click="submit">             │
  │    Motiver meg! 🚀              │
  │  </button>                      │
  │                                 │
  │  <MotivatorCard v-if="result"   │  ← Shows result after API call
  │    :data="result" />            │
  └─────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Step 4 — Create `components/MotivatorPicker.vue`
- Renders a row/grid of selectable motivator cards from the motivators list.
- Each card shows name + optional avatar.
- Emits the selected motivator via `v-model`.
- Highlights the active selection.

### Step 5 — Create `composables/useMotivator.ts`
- Expose reactive refs: `task`, `selectedMotivator`, `result`, `loading`.
- Computed `canSubmit`: true when `task` is non-empty AND `selectedMotivator` is set.
- `submit()` calls `$fetch('/api/motivate', { method: 'POST', body: { task, motivator: selectedMotivator.id, personality, language, contentTypes } })`.
- Default personality to `"balanced"`, language to `"no"`, contentTypes to `["humor", "facts", "quotes"]`.

### Step 6 — Create `components/MotivatorCard.vue`
- Receives the API response as a prop.
- Displays: motivational message, fun fact, tip, quote (with author), and a GIF.
- Use Tailwind for card-style layout with rounded corners, padding, and shadow.

### Step 7 — Style with Tailwind CSS
- Mobile-first responsive design (the wireframe looks phone-sized).
- Center content vertically and horizontally.
- Large, bold heading (`text-4xl font-bold`).
- Speech bubble styling for the question text (rounded bg, tail/arrow via CSS).
- Motivator cards: bordered, rounded, with a ring/highlight on selection.
- Friendly color palette (Itera brand or warm/inviting tones).

### Step 8 — Add the face illustration
- Option A: Use a simple SVG/emoji character placed in `public/` or inline.
- Option B: Use an AI-generated or hand-drawn avatar image in `public/face.svg`.
- Position it above the speech bubble, centered.

### Step 9 — Wire up `SettingsPanel.vue` (later step)
- Not in the wireframe, but planned in the architecture.
- Can be added as a collapsible panel or a gear icon that opens a modal.
- Controls: personality mode, language toggle (no/en), content type checkboxes.

